In the previous lesson, we have tried out regresion model and also learned methods of how to diagnose the model. As you have seen, very often, simply fitting the dependent variable with all independent variables does not always give reasonably good result. Indeed, most of time, it gives very poor fitting. In this lesson, we will discuss how to improve the model.

Simple Method

From the summary() function, we can tell which independent variables are not linearly related to the the dependent variable. We may just consider removing them from the model. Letâs use ToyatoaCorolla data again.

#read in data
cars<-read.csv("ToyotaCorolla.csv")
cars <- cars[,c(-4)]    

fit <- lm(Price ~., data=cars)
summary(fit)

Some outliers can be identified. We may examine these outliers closely and identify some factors that make them outliers. If we are able to identify such factors, we can then try to introduce new variable(s) into the dataset and improve the model. Examining outliers sometimes turn out to very valuable. It may help to identify some insights unknown previously. However, if these outliers cannot be explained or sometimes purely due to data entry error, we may consider remove them from the model. Multicollinearity

To our common knowledge, for a second hand car, the older it is, more KM that it has travelled. Heavier a car is, more CC it should have. This can be validated from the correlation between them:

cor(cars2$Age,cars2$KM)
## [1] 0.5073977
cor(cars2$CC,cars2$Weight)
## [1] 0.6756669

In case two highly correlated variables are included in a model, it may be problematic. For example, it may make regression coefficients of these variables insignificant while they are supposed to be significant. Or it may lead to unreasonable interpretation of the coefficients. For example, the coefficient of CC is negative in the model, which means higher the CC is, cheaper the car is. Obviously this does not sound correct. The problem is called multicollinearity. Letâs see what happens if Weight is removed from the model.

cars3<-cars2[,c(-6)]
fit3<-lm(Price~.,data=cars3)
summary(fit3)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Price ~ ., data = cars3)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -4853.0  -929.1   -52.4   825.0 10469.5 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  1.354e+04  4.606e+02  29.397   <2e-16 ***
## Age         -1.453e+02  2.598e+00 -55.927   <2e-16 ***

## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1468 on 1423 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.8302, Adjusted R-squared:  0.8297 
## F-statistic:  1740 on 4 and 1423 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Multicollinearity can be detected using a stastic called the variance inflation factor (VIF). For any predicator variable, the square root of the VIF indicates the degree to which the confidence interval for the variableâs regression parameter is expanded relative to a model with uncorrelated predicators. As a general rule, sqrt(vif)>2 indicates a multicollinearity problem.

vif(fit2)
##      Age       KM       HP       CC   Weight 
## 1.952424 1.886179 1.164443 2.316821 2.594238
sqrt(vif(fit2)) > 2  #any problem?
##    Age     KM     HP     CC Weight 
##  FALSE  FALSE  FALSE  FALSE  FALSE

The test tells no multicollinearity problem. Having correlated variables in a model is not a problem if your objective is just to predict the dependent variable. However, it will cause difficulty in explaining the variables.

Variable selection

Suppose your data set has a lot of variables, it becomes a very tedious job to manually adjust and test the varaibles to be included in the model. Two popular approaches are used to automatically select a final set of predicator variables.

Stepwise Regression

In stepwise selection, variables are added to or deleted from a model one at a time, until some stopping criteria is reached. For example, in forward stepwise regression, you add predictor variables to the model one at a time, until adding any variable no longer improves the model. In backward stepwise regression, you start with a model with all independent variables and delete predicator variables one at a time, until deleting any variable no longer improves the model. In stepwise stepwise regression, you combine the two approaches.

One stopping criterion used is the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC), which takes into account a modelâs statistical fit and the number of parameters needed to achieve this fit. Models with smaller AIC values - indicating adequate fit with fewer parameters - are preferred. MASS package provides functions to perform variable selection using AIC.

library(MASS)
stepAIC(fit, direction = "backward")

Cross Validation

So far, our focus has been on deriving a model that could be used to interpret the relationship between dependent variable and the independent variables. However, if your ultimate objective is prediction, then you should care more about the performance of the model in predicting new data. In this section, we are going to introduce a method called Cross-Validation to evaluate the generalizability of a regression equation.

In Cross-Validation, a portion of the data is selected as the training sample, and a portion is selected as the hold-out sample. A regression model is developed on the training sample, and then applied to the hold-out sample to validate its performance.

In k-fold cross-validation, the sample is divided into k subsamples. Each of the k subsamples serves as a hold-out group, and the combined observations from the remaining k-1 subsamples serve as the training group. The preformance for the k prediction equations applied to the k hold out samples is recorded and then averaged.

The following function can be used for this purpose:

shrinkage <- function(fit, k=10){
    require(bootstrap)
    theta.fit <- function(x,y) {lsfit(x,y)}
    theta.predict<-function(fit, x) {cbind(1,x) %*%fit$coef}
    
    x<-fit$model[,2:ncol(fit$model)]
    y<-fit$model[,1]
    results<-crossval(x,y,theta.fit,theta.predict,ngroup=k)
    r2<-cor(y,fit$fitted.values)^2
    r2cv<-cor(y,results$cv.fit)^2
    cat("Original R-square =", r2, "\n")
    cat(k, "Fold Cross-Validated R-Square = ",r2cv,"\n")
    cat("Change =", r2-r2cv,"\n")
}

Now, letâs compare the models done above:

shrinkage(fit)
## Loading required package: bootstrap
## Original R-square = 0.8654038 
## 10 Fold Cross-Validated R-Square =  0.8585361 
## Change = 0.006867646
shrinkage(fit1)
## Original R-square = 0.8650265 
## 10 Fold Cross-Validated R-Square =  0.8591982 
## Change = 0.005828336
shrinkage(fit5)

Relative Importance

A common question that a manager will ask is âWhat is the most important factor in the model?â It is quite obvious that we cannot use the coefficients. The simplest approach has been to compare standardized regression coeeficients, which describe the expected chaneg in the response variable (expressed in standard deviation units) for a standard deviation change in a predictor variable, holding the other variables constant. You can obtain the standardized regression coefficient in R by standardizing each of the variables in your dataset to a mean of 0 and standard deviation of 1 using the scale() function, before submitting the dataset to a regression analysis. For example,

zcars1 <- as.data.frame(scale(cars1))
zfit<-lm(Price~.,data=zcars1)
coef(zfit)
##   (Intercept)           Age            KM            HP            CC 
## -1.012096e-15 -6.262975e-01 -1.738937e-01  1.341007e-01 -8.393559e-02 
##        Weight 
##  3.243686e-01

You can see that âAgeâ is the most important factor in deciding the resale price of Toyota Corolla. A one-standard-deviation increase in car age will decrease the car price by 0.626 standard deviation.
